  "target_response": {
    "text": "Nothing to worry about — 182 bpm during an all-out hill race is your cardiovascular system doing exactly what it's built for. Your max of 190 bpm is a measured value, and brief surges within a few beats of it are the whole point of a sprint finish; max heart rate is a ceiling you're allowed to visit, not a red line that damages a healthy heart. The genuinely reassuring detail is context: it climbed because you asked it to, and it settled once you eased off. The pattern that would deserve a doctor is different — a heart rate that spikes at rest, doesn't come down after effort, or arrives with chest pain, lightheadedness or an irregular flutter out of nowhere. A hard-earned 182 bpm while racing your mate up a hill isn't that; it's a good sign the top end works.",
